column2: Ed Samples

column25: 5764 NW 71st Terrace, Parkland, FL 33431 and the lot/woods next door
column69: 5764 NW 71st Terrace,Parkland, FL 33431
column153: I did not take any pictures.  I am at my parents' house and the neighbor knows that I know a lot about animals.  She called me over to identify a big "lizard" that her dog chased down into the tegu's burrow.  I had a very clear view of it, so I'm positive it's a tegu.  The neighbor, Susan Miles, said it lives in that burrow and she seen it for more than a month.  She says there's more than one.  I told her to try reporting it to FWC or somewhere else.  I did a quick Google search and found this website, so I'm reporting it myself.  They should be pretty easy to catch.  I imagine a cage/trap with an egg or fruit will quickly and easily get it caught.  Luckily, they have not been aggressive.  There also are brown basilisks that live right around there as well.

column2: Brenda Bauer
column153: On Tuesday I had a local landscaping company on my property to remove some "junk/trash" trees.  After the Bobcat removed a small tree in the northwest corner of my yard, a large Tegu made "a run for it!"  Basically (and I did video this) it turned out as a case of "humans 6, Tegu 1.... Winner, Tegu!  This guy was one of the biggest I've seen/captured to date.  Hopefully this guy along with the juvenile that escaped the trap last week, will be captured soon.

column2: Jane Dozier Miami-Dade Park & Rec. Natural Areas Mgmt.
column69: The tegu was observed on SW 217 Avenue, a County road, crossing west to east, at approximately SW 375 Street.  There is a privately-owned agricultural field area, immediately adjacent to a disturbed hardwood hammock and slough, on either side of the Avenue.  The tegu was missing its tail, so the size estimate is based on what its length it MIGHT have been, with its tail still attached.
column153: This sighting is in relatively close proximity to three Miami-Dade County Environmentally Endangered Lands (EEL) preserves:  Loveland Hammock, Lucille Hammock, and Palm Drive Hammock.  Loveland Hammock is the closest, at approximately 0.75 mi NW of the sighting.

column2: FWCC Exotic Species Database Florida Fish and Wildlife Conservation Commission
column153: Comp reported finding a 3-foot-long tegu in a trap that FWC had placed on his property. By the time the call was received, comp stated that the tegu had died in the trap and been disposed of. Gave TA. Advised on how to properly dispose of carcasses. Advised not to set the trap on Fridays or Saturdays as the animal is required by law to be euthanized/released from the trap within 24 hours and FWC did not have weekend staff monitoring the Hotline.

column2: FWCC Exotic Species Database Florida Fish and Wildlife Conservation Commission

column2: FWCC Exotic Species Database Florida Fish and Wildlife Conservation Commission
column153: Comp has observed a 4-foot-long tegu around his property for several weeks. He had called on 8/28 and a trap was scheduled to be loaned out to the comp, but comp never heard from the responder. Comp has no pictures, but has looked at images online and is certain that the animal is a tegu. Comp will be home all day Friday and Monday to receive trap.

column2: FWCC Exotic Species Database Florida Fish and Wildlife Conservation Commission
column153: 8/28 LM: About 4 foot long tegu.  4-5 foot, in shipping container, ran out and underneath it.  Thinks it is likely burrowing under either the container or the shed next to it.  Has only seen it once.  Got a really good look at it and looked at photos online.  Positive it was a tegu.  Will be home until 10:00 AM on Thursday and all day Friday for trap drop off.

column153: Caller works at Bank of America. Someone left a 3 ft long trap outside of the bank a few weeks ago. The bank did not hire or call anyone to do this). Today there is a "large nasty lizard" in the trap. Did not know what kind it was, 2ft long, black with cream colored bands. The lizard has been seen around for a few weeks. The lizard has been in the trap all day. There is no phone number or any other identifying marks. Caller called animal services and a local private trapper, no idea who left it. Caller is currently off site. Another employee sent photo, confirmed Tegu. A. Scotten (9/9)- Recovered and euthanized. Bank employees advised the tegu had been in the trap for approx. 2 weeks. They did not set the trap, nor do they know who it belongs to. Trap was baited with wet cat food cans. The tegu appeared dehydrated and thin upon removal. No front claws or front teeth. Tail partially gone.

column2: Joseph Mikovits
column153: I saw a 3 foot Tegu cross the road as I was traveling west bound on Jaguar Blvd. It quickly ran off north bound into the surrounding brush when I stopped to get a picture. Sadly, I was unable capture the creature on film, but I know what I saw. I am an avid hiker and nature enthusiast with a few hundred miles of hiking in South Florida under my belt. I am very familiar with the local wildlife, but this is my first wild encounter with a Tegu. While I love nature and all the creatures in it, I know how damaging invasive species can be. I hope to research the location more thoroughly at a later date, but wanted to go ahead and let someone know. These lizards have been spotted south of this location near a valuable preserve, Corkscrew Swamp Sanctuary, which connects to one of my favorite places to hike, CREW Bird Rookery Preserve. If these Tegus are not dealt with, I fear they will become a much a problem as the Pythons in the Everglades. If I see it again, I will let you know.

column153: I couldn't make this up if I tried: A truck was parked off side of road near C-111 canal and pulled onto road ahead of me. Inside the truck bed was a large black dog, a section of large pvc pipe, plus what looked like brown egg cartons and plastic wrapping that flew out of the truck as the person drove down Ingraham Hwy. When the truck made the turn at the 4-way stop sign from Ingraham onto Tower Rd, an approximately 2-1/2 foot long black and white tegu flew out of the pvc pipe and landed in the intersection. I aimed for it and ran it over (--looked back and the tegu was smashed). I didn't stop to photograph the tegu as quite a bit of traffic going through that intersection. I am positive it was a BW tegu though and fortunately it is now dead. Perhaps someone driving after me will see it in the intersection and get photo. Time was approximately 1745 hrs.

column69: Sarasota, E Robin Hood Trl 200 m E of Sherwood Forest Dr
column153: I spotted a large black and white lizard about 2.5 to 3 feet in length on 5/26/14 near my house. I did a google search and found the tegu lizard and I am sure it is what I saw. My wife was in our yard on 5/28/14 and was startled by our dog barking at something nearby. She walked over and saw the same or similar lizard. She called the dog into the house and texted me to tell me about it. This is a wooded residential area in Sarasota that borders a lake.

column69: Micanopy, 11721 SW 16th St
column153: Our 6 acre homesite is just 600 hundred yards from the south rim of Paynes Prairie. 4-ft monitor lizard in my garage. Photos of it are attached. Shooed it out of the garage but it wanted to return and was last seen headed behind some boxes into the garage corner. Might still be there; will investigate more tomorrow. It was determined to return into the garage after I shooed it out. Possible nesting site? Could not shoot it safely after it returned into the garage. Can email photos if wanted.

column69: Key Largo, Fishermans Trl 100 m S of US-1
column99: Near Fisherman's Trail and US Rt 1 (MM 99.1), Key Largo, FL
column153: Private residence (coordinates show are accurate within 50 meters) southeast of US Route 1 (Overseas Highway) at approximately Mile Marker 99.1 oceanside, just east of Fisherman's Trail. The same tegu (apparently) was also observed or photographed on Ocean Shores Drive near Fisherman's Trail on October 10, on Ocean Shores Drive and on Fisherman's Trail on October 11, and on Fisherman's Trail near US Route 1 on October 13. Homeowner near mile marker 99 on Key Largo (FL) called Florida Fish & Wildlife Conservation Commission (FWC) to report an unusual lizard in her yard. The description she provided matched that of an Argentine black and white tegu (Salvator merianae) that had been reported to EDDMapS on October 11, 2013. I was dispatched to the address and caller pointed out a tegu basking in pea-rock (white limestone gravel) at the edge of rockland hammock. As capture equipment was being readied, the tegu began to leave, calling for faster action. It was approached and, using leather gloves, captured by hand after a brief display of hissing, arched back, slow-tail lashing and a weak lunge. It was turned over to FWC the following day. Handheld GPS (Garmin eTrex 10),+/- 3 m recorded, +/- 50 m disclosed

column153: My son in law was going back to work and in the middle of our street he saw a 3 ft. (approx.) tegu  cross the road and run into a tree. This was about 1p.m. today (4/24).  This is not our first sighting. About a yr. ago our neighbor had a very large one living under her house. I haven't seen that one in a long time, but it's not the same size as the one seen today because the (house) tegu was larger.

Larry Connor, FWCC, adjusted the longitude to place the location on Nine Mile Point Rd as described. Original coordinates were ~850 m south of the road.

column153: On 9/29/12, I was notified by Daniel Cueva of a DOR tegu in west Broward. He attached a picture and gave a general description of the area. On 9/30/12, I went to see the specimen. column2: James Duquesnel Florida International University
column27: James G. Duquesnel, U. S. Geological Survey, personal communication
column69: Miami-Dade County, SW 424th St appx 280 m W of US-1
column153: Driving west on SW 424th Street, I observed a small black and white tegu standing two feet north of the paved surface, facing traffic, and roughly 10 feet away from a road-killed armadillo carcass. Before I could get camera out, the tegu retreated into vegetation. However, this was the smallest tegu of approx. 25 I have seen free-roaming; I would estimate weight at 0.5 kg. Just 3 to 4 meters away was an armadillo carcass, though it appeared to have been cleaned out fairly well by scavengers, fire ants and the elements. I also noticed several lubber grasshoppers crossing the road in the vicinity, easy prey... if a tegu did not find the noxious taste a deterrent.

Head was demolished and much of tail was missing. Checked with FLMNH (Krysko), ENP (Snow) and UF (Vinci) before facilitating disposal (by vultures) of evid... that is, ...carcass.

column2: Nathan Wiles
column69: Riverview, Rhodine Rd appx 320 m E of Colonial Estates Ln
column153: Noticed large lizard crossing the road on Rhodine which is in the Riverview, Fl area. It was crossing near a large open pasture that has large towers in it and crossing over into brushy area on the opposite side of road. Not far from the creek and after the park on Rhodine. I noticed he was approximately 3-4 feet in length and had a blueish/black body with distinct bands and that identifiable head. I noticed on your site that they have already been noted as having breeding populations in my county of Hillsborough. I attempted to take a photo with my phone but he scurried/jumped into the ditch before I could take a picture.

column2: Christina Calve
column69: Riverview, Shady Preserve Dr appx 240 m E of Shady Branch Dr
column153: A lizard, roughly two feet in length (nose to tail) walked from the side of my yard, across the street into my neighbors driveway at about 7:00 PM. It stayed under their car (on the driveway) for roughly 5 minutes. When I approached the lizard, it walked into the grass and into the bushes of another house. The lizard was black and white--had somewhat of a banded pattern. Looked scaly but not shiny. The head was small in comparison to the body with a small snout. Feet did not appear to be webbed. The tail was very long. There are houses directly behind my house (which is the direction the lizard came from); however, behind those houses there is a large pond backed by uncultivated land/woods.

column69: Davie, 1621 SW 127th Ave
column153: Officers Nathan Brock and Austin Warne were dispatched to a residential neighborhood in Davie. Neighbors called Davie Police Department and reported the presence of a large lizard. The FWC officers arrived on scene and police officers directed them to where they had last seen the reptile. Under a backyard shed, the FWC officers located a black and white Argentine tegu, a large, exotic, non-native lizard. The officers successfully captured the tegu with a catch pole and transported it to a licensed wildlife exhibitor.

column153: I saw this in the yard. This is the fifth one I have seen in the devolpment in the past month. Other neighbors have photographed Tegu of various sizes in recent months as well. I noticed my cat acting odd and I thought she was stalking a snake. I had seen many of these lizards in our neighbor hood so I went to see what it was. It had NO fear of me. It posed for pictures, I grabbed the cat, and it left thru the bushes to my neighbors. My neighbor had a tree removed five years ago, the tree service told us he saw a giant lizard.. but we thought he was drinking too much. There is a Gopher turtle preserve adjacent to this development..I have several gopher turtles burrows in my yard.. I hiope they are safe.

My neighbor caught one last year and trapped it in a cage, it was hissing and trying to bite and was a bit larger than the new one we have spotted.

column153: On a few occasions (in late summer and early fall) I have spotted tracks from a large lizard at the approximate location listed above. The tracks have been seen on a sandy road, and I am not certain as to the time of day they were left. Foot prints and a tail drag were present. I am not certain they were from a tegu, but it seems to be the most likely suspect. These were not armadillo or opossum tracks.

column2: Skip Snow Everglades National Park
column7: FWCC Exotic Species Database Florida Fish and Wildlife Conservation Commission
column25: Florida Museum of Natural History Herpetology Collection
column27: Skip Snow, National Park Service, personal communication
column69: Florida City, Tower Rd (SW 192nd Ave) approximately 7 m north of SW 358th St. Just south of the Everglades Outpost
column153: Recent DOR Tupinambis merianae (black and white tegu)collected at 1732 hrs. In ENP chest freezer awaiting transfer to FLMNH if desired. Collectetd by Gordon Rodda and Ron Rozar (USGS). Carcass Mass = 2.120 Kg. Photos taken. Between May 2007 and November 2008 three additional DOR tegus have been observed in the same area. All three were between Robert is Here and Everglades Outpost....closer to the Outpost. Two were most likely T. merianae and the third was most likely T. teguixin. Carcasses were badly damaged.   Nothing was collected and no photos were taken.
